    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "yeah it's definitely looking like nitrogen. i tried adding some compost but i'm worried the soil might be too acidic for it to actually work. how can i figure out if the pH is off and how do i fix it if it is?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You'll need a soil test kit, which is the most reliable way to check your soil's pH level. These kits are usually inexpensive and tell you exactly what your soil is doing, which is much better than guessing. If the pH is too acidic or too alkaline for your tomatoes (which generally prefer a slightly acidic to neutral range, around 6.0 to 6.8), you can adjust it. To raise the pH (make it less acidic), you can mix in agricultural lime, and to lower it (make it more acidic), you can use elemental sulfur.",
      "source": "target",
